rComments: One of the best profs at U of T. He is intimidatingly smart, yet still extremely approachable. He gave me some of the best advice about essays I've ever had. CLass discussions were consistently engaging and interesting. He really cares about literature and his students, and it shows.

Bad course. Hopefully this professor just did not have any time to plan the course. The course had no direction. What was this course about? I don't know. I read his books to try to figure out this guy's angle. He was very concerned about what people were really trying say (great) but had no clear or better direction in what he was saying.

Best prof ever! Prof Knight encourages intellectual and insightful participation and discussion. His assignments inspire creativity rather than stunt it. He is also one of the most welcoming and most helpful profs in the department!

His course on creative criticism is very interesting and is probably the best class I've taken during my time at the university. He is very insightful and engages the class in a Socratic manner. Fair marker and provides good feedback.

Prof Knight is so helpful, funny and thought-provoking. His course content was interesting and he lead a 3rd year course in a seminar-style fashion, which was awesome. One of the best professors I've ever had

Really helpful professor, eager to meet with students and give feedback on essays and tests or advice as needed. Was able to lead great discussion even with a fairly large class. Great sense of humour and a compelling speaker.

This professor drove me crazy. He'd ask what you thought and you might say "Derrida is convoluted" and he'd say "I don't think Derrida is convoluted" and move on. OF COURSE YOU DON'T THINK HE IS CONVOLUTED. YOU'RE A LITERARY THEORIST. Only the people who understood the material got any real attention because they could drive the discussion further.

Knight is very friendly and approachable, with a great sense of humour and enthusiasm in course material. Although Knight makes sure each student is given an opportunity to speak, the class would benefit from being smaller. Overall, a great professor.
